1
00:00:03,295 --> 00:00:07,257
No one can crush my curiosity and passion.

2
00:00:07,633 --> 00:00:09,676
My curiosity never dies!

3
00:00:10,844 --> 00:00:13,805
The customer should be here soon.

4
00:00:13,889 --> 00:00:16,266
SEVENTH BOOK:
<i>THE GIRL WHO WROTE LONELINESS</i>

5
00:00:17,351 --> 00:00:18,185
What's all this?

6
00:00:20,604 --> 00:00:22,147
DELICIOUS FOOD FOR THE SOUL

7
00:00:27,653 --> 00:00:29,613
- Hello.
- Oh, what?

8
00:00:30,572 --> 00:00:31,907
Who are you?

9
00:00:31,990 --> 00:00:35,118
PARK SANG-YOUNG, NOVELIST
I'm here to sell a book.

10
00:00:35,202 --> 00:00:37,704
- - You're here to sell a book?
- Yes, I am.

11
00:00:37,788 --> 00:00:38,872
Hold on!

12
00:00:39,623 --> 00:00:41,542
- - It's you, right?
- Sorry?

13
00:00:41,792 --> 00:00:43,085
That novel!

14
00:00:43,585 --> 00:00:45,337
You're a great author!

15
00:00:45,420 --> 00:00:47,422
- - Well, I guess.
- Oh, my goodness.

16
00:00:47,506 --> 00:00:48,674
Come take a seat.

17
00:00:48,757 --> 00:00:49,967
- - Right here?
- Yes.

18
00:00:51,885 --> 00:00:52,970
You're an author, aren't you?

19
00:00:53,053 --> 00:00:55,138
- - Yes, I am an author.
- Right? I knew it.

20
00:00:55,222 --> 00:00:57,266
Let me introduce this place.

21
00:00:57,349 --> 00:01:00,018
This is the cutest neighborhood
in the world,

22
00:01:00,102 --> 00:01:01,937
Kangho-dong.

23
00:01:02,020 --> 00:01:03,730
Here, I read people like books.

24
00:01:03,856 --> 00:01:05,732
This is Hodong's Bookshop. Welcome.

25
00:01:05,816 --> 00:01:07,526
Yes. It's nice to meet you.

26
00:01:08,527 --> 00:01:10,821
- - You look familiar.
- Right.

27
00:01:10,904 --> 00:01:12,197
You were on a lot of TV shows, right?

28
00:01:12,281 --> 00:01:13,574
That's right.

29
00:01:13,657 --> 00:01:14,908
- - Yes.
- I was

30
00:01:14,992 --> 00:01:17,828
on five shows as a regular cast member.

31
00:01:17,911 --> 00:01:19,288
- - As a regular cast member?
- Yes.

32
00:01:19,371 --> 00:01:21,415
But surprisingly, no one recognizes me.

33
00:01:21,498 --> 00:01:23,834
- - Considering the frequency of exposure?
- Yes.

34
00:01:24,209 --> 00:01:27,796
Even though I've been on a lot of shows
on most broadcast channels...

35
00:01:27,880 --> 00:01:29,381
- - No one recognizes you?
- No.

36
00:01:29,464 --> 00:01:31,717
You're such a famous author, though.

37
00:01:31,800 --> 00:01:33,302
When I take a look at you,

38
00:01:33,385 --> 00:01:34,803
you don't look like an author.

39
00:01:34,887 --> 00:01:37,139
Right, you would never guess I write.

40
00:01:37,306 --> 00:01:38,599
It surprises a lot of people.

41
00:01:38,682 --> 00:01:40,893
- - Are you sure we've never met before?
- It does feel familiar.

42
00:01:40,976 --> 00:01:43,228
I hope you don't mind me saying this,

43
00:01:43,312 --> 00:01:46,565
but I kind of feel
like I'm looking into a mirror.

44
00:01:46,857 --> 00:01:48,859
- - There's something familiar about you.
- Right.

45
00:01:48,942 --> 00:01:51,862
Your demeanor feels very familiar.
I see it all the time.

46
00:01:51,945 --> 00:01:53,405
The way your lips are pursed,

47
00:01:53,488 --> 00:01:55,282
the way you move, and so on.

48
00:01:57,075 --> 00:01:58,243
Now, let's get into it.

49
00:01:58,327 --> 00:01:59,912
What's your name?

50
00:01:59,995 --> 00:02:02,247
- - My name is Park Sang-young.
- Right.

51
00:02:02,331 --> 00:02:03,165
And your pen name?

52
00:02:03,248 --> 00:02:05,667
- - I don't have one. I use my real name.
- I see.

53
00:02:05,876 --> 00:02:10,130
I wanted to make my name
known to the world.

54
00:02:10,214 --> 00:02:12,341
That desire to seek attention motivated me

55
00:02:12,424 --> 00:02:14,718
- - It did?
- to use my own name.

56
00:02:14,801 --> 00:02:16,553
Who gave you your name?

57
00:02:16,637 --> 00:02:18,347
My uncle...

58
00:02:18,430 --> 00:02:19,264
HESITATING

59
00:02:19,348 --> 00:02:21,350
...sought a guru similar to you.

60
00:02:21,975 --> 00:02:23,352
That's where he got it.

61
00:02:23,435 --> 00:02:24,394
HOCRATES WAS ONCE THE KNEE-DROP GURU

62
00:02:24,478 --> 00:02:26,063
He paid handsomely for it.

63
00:02:26,146 --> 00:02:27,940
- - A guru similar to me?
- Yes.

64
00:02:28,023 --> 00:02:31,068
Someone from your previous profession.

65
00:02:31,652 --> 00:02:33,403
- - Your eyes disappear when you smile.
- Yes.

66
00:02:33,820 --> 00:02:35,614
- - People like us
- Yes.

67
00:02:36,073 --> 00:02:37,241
have to smile,

68
00:02:37,324 --> 00:02:38,659
- - That's right.
- or we look scary.

69
00:02:38,742 --> 00:02:40,661
- - People think I'm angry.
- Right.

70
00:02:40,744 --> 00:02:42,955
- - Even when I'm calm and happy,
- Right.

71
00:02:43,038 --> 00:02:45,499
people ask me if I'm feeling all right.

72
00:02:45,582 --> 00:02:47,334
- - You just weren't smiling.
- Right.

73
00:02:47,417 --> 00:02:49,294
I just wasn't smiling. That's all.

74
00:02:49,378 --> 00:02:52,297
Did you practice your smile in the mirror
to look likable?

75
00:02:52,381 --> 00:02:54,716
- - I never practiced. I was born with it.
- I see.

76
00:02:54,800 --> 00:02:56,343
- - You know what?
- What?

77
00:02:56,426 --> 00:02:57,594
I hope you don't mind me saying this,

78
00:02:57,678 --> 00:02:59,471
but you're either born cute or not.

79
00:02:59,555 --> 00:03:02,891
You're right. I couldn't agree more.

80
00:03:02,975 --> 00:03:04,434
Pursed lips like ours

81
00:03:04,643 --> 00:03:08,063
can't be learned or performed.

82
00:03:08,146 --> 00:03:10,023
- - What are "pursed lips"?
- Pursed lips.

83
00:03:10,107 --> 00:03:11,400
Pursed lips.

84
00:03:11,483 --> 00:03:12,693
It's your specialty.

85
00:03:12,776 --> 00:03:15,028
You've been doing it for 30 years.

86
00:03:15,153 --> 00:03:16,905
You have to be born with that.

87
00:03:17,781 --> 00:03:18,824
GOODNESS

88
00:03:19,241 --> 00:03:21,660
Could you tell me
what your best-known work is?

89
00:03:21,743 --> 00:03:22,870
My best-known work?

90
00:03:22,953 --> 00:03:25,789
It's called <i>Love in the Big City</i>.

91
00:03:25,873 --> 00:03:30,085
Many people remember it
by Kim Go-eun's smile in the film poster.

92
00:03:30,460 --> 00:03:33,922
I'm the author who wrote the novel
that the film is based on.

93
00:03:34,173 --> 00:03:36,508
It was also adapted as a TV series.

94
00:03:36,592 --> 00:03:39,428
I wrote the script for that myself.

95
00:03:39,928 --> 00:03:40,762
A BESTSELLER THAT SOLD 150,000 COPIES!

96
00:03:40,846 --> 00:03:43,891
BOOKS THAT SELL OVER 10,000 COPIES
ARE CONSIDERED BESTSELLERS

97
00:03:43,974 --> 00:03:46,810
IT WAS SO POPULAR THAT IT RECEIVED
FILM AND SERIES ADAPTATIONS!

98
00:03:47,102 --> 00:03:48,520
I think I'm in love.

99
00:03:48,896 --> 00:03:50,063
A NOVEL ABOUT HOW YOUTH IN THE BIG CITY
Are you seriously talking about "love"?

100
00:03:50,147 --> 00:03:51,523
<i>It's all because of dopamine.</i>

101
00:03:51,607 --> 00:03:53,859
LOVE IN MANY DIFFERENT FORMS
<i>Instead of worrying about those things,</i>

102
00:03:53,942 --> 00:03:55,527
I'm going to do everything I can.

103
00:03:55,611 --> 00:03:56,945
SANG-YOUNG'S SPECIAL STORY ABOUT LOVE
<i>I thought it was foolish</i>

104
00:03:57,029 --> 00:03:58,238
RECEIVED SCREEN ADAPTATIONS
<i>to believe</i>

105
00:03:58,322 --> 00:04:00,532
AND CAPTIVATED READERS ALL OVER THE WORLD
<i>there'd be everlasting love.</i>

106
00:04:00,616 --> 00:04:02,576
<i>Even though you're together,</i>
<i>it doesn't feel that way.</i>

107
00:04:03,827 --> 00:04:05,162
You watched both, right?

108
00:04:05,245 --> 00:04:07,748
I watched them carefully multiple times.

109
00:04:07,831 --> 00:04:10,042
So, the film versus the series.

110
00:04:10,125 --> 00:04:11,418
Which did you like more?

111
00:04:11,502 --> 00:04:12,544
I liked the series more.

112
00:04:13,754 --> 00:04:14,838
Because I wrote it.

113
00:04:15,923 --> 00:04:18,967
THE AUTHOR HAS NO HESITATION IN CHOOSING

114
00:04:19,593 --> 00:04:21,261
Was Kim Go-eun's acting

115
00:04:21,345 --> 00:04:23,305
- - not good enough?
- That's not what I meant.

116
00:04:23,388 --> 00:04:25,599
- - Why didn't you like the film?
- No, it's not that.

117
00:04:25,682 --> 00:04:27,142
- - I loved the film.
- Okay.

118
00:04:27,226 --> 00:04:29,603
I really enjoyed it. I mean it.

119
00:04:29,686 --> 00:04:31,897
When I saw Go-eun on the screen,

120
00:04:31,980 --> 00:04:36,568
<i>she was portraying Jae-hee</i>
<i>exactly as I imagined her.</i>

121
00:04:36,652 --> 00:04:38,946
It's like she came right out of my spine.

122
00:04:39,029 --> 00:04:40,697
- - Really?
- Yes.

123
00:04:40,781 --> 00:04:42,533
I seriously got the chills.

124
00:04:42,616 --> 00:04:44,618
- - Are you watching, Go-eun? I love you.
- Then...

125
00:04:46,078 --> 00:04:48,664
HE THOUGHT THE GUEST WOULD BE MORE SERIOUS
SINCE HE'S A NOVELIST

126
00:04:48,747 --> 00:04:50,040
You don't hesitate.

127
00:04:50,123 --> 00:04:52,918
I love her. I really love Go-eun.

128
00:04:53,418 --> 00:04:55,170
But in spite of that,

129
00:04:55,254 --> 00:04:56,964
because it's queer literature,

130
00:04:57,047 --> 00:04:59,216
in terms of depicting queer experiences,

131
00:04:59,299 --> 00:05:01,718
<i>it was done a bit better</i>
<i>in the series adaptation.</i>

132
00:05:01,802 --> 00:05:03,136
THE SERIES WAS CLOSER TO THE ORIGINAL

133
00:05:03,554 --> 00:05:05,305
Please brag about the awards you won.

134
00:05:05,389 --> 00:05:07,015
- - The awards?
- Yes.

135
00:05:07,099 --> 00:05:09,268
- - You have many.
- I debuted in 2016.

136
00:05:09,351 --> 00:05:10,769
I was in my late twenties.

137
00:05:10,853 --> 00:05:13,063
- - There's a publisher called Munhakdongne.
- Yes.

138
00:05:13,146 --> 00:05:15,190
It's one of the biggest in Korea.

139
00:05:15,274 --> 00:05:17,192
- - Right.
- Yes, I won

140
00:05:17,276 --> 00:05:20,320
<i>their New Author Award that year.</i>

141
00:05:20,404 --> 00:05:22,656
- <i>- Right, I see.</i>
<i>- I debuted through that.</i>

142
00:05:22,739 --> 00:05:26,243
<i>I also won the Grand Prize</i>
<i>of the Young Author Award</i>

143
00:05:26,326 --> 00:05:28,579
and the Sin Dong-yup Prize for Literature.

144
00:05:28,662 --> 00:05:30,581
I was also on the 9 o'clock news once.

145
00:05:30,664 --> 00:05:32,124
I wondered what it was for.

146
00:05:32,207 --> 00:05:35,419
ONE OF THE WORLD'S TOP 3 LITERARY AWARDS
<i>It was for the International Booker Prize,</i>

147
00:05:36,295 --> 00:05:37,838
- - which I didn't win,
- I see.

148
00:05:37,921 --> 00:05:40,465
- - but I received a nomination in 2022.
- You were nominated.

149
00:05:40,549 --> 00:05:43,343
Yes, <i>Love in the Big City</i>

150
00:05:43,427 --> 00:05:45,220
was nominated for it.

151
00:05:45,304 --> 00:05:47,931
The Booker Prize is hosted in the UK.

152
00:05:48,015 --> 00:05:49,766
- - Yes.
- It's highly prestigious.

153
00:05:49,850 --> 00:05:52,060
It wasn't international before, was it?

154
00:05:52,227 --> 00:05:53,770
No, the international prize
was created recently.

155
00:05:53,854 --> 00:05:56,190
- - Right, I heard.
- The first winner after the change

156
00:05:56,273 --> 00:05:57,941
- - was Han Kang.
- Right.

157
00:05:58,025 --> 00:06:00,402
She won with <i>The Vegetarian</i>.

158
00:06:00,485 --> 00:06:05,365
I recall it wasn't long since the
International Booker Prize was announced.

159
00:06:05,532 --> 00:06:07,409
When I was nominated for that,

160
00:06:07,576 --> 00:06:09,578
it felt amazing.

161
00:06:10,037 --> 00:06:11,205
Even after that,

162
00:06:11,288 --> 00:06:14,249
there was the Dublin Literary Award
and the Prix Médicis.

163
00:06:14,333 --> 00:06:17,669
I was nominated
for those European literary awards.

164
00:06:18,420 --> 00:06:21,465
So, many people have been reading my work.

165
00:06:22,382 --> 00:06:24,343
- - I feel awkward saying it.
- It's okay.

166
00:06:24,426 --> 00:06:26,345
- - You need to promote yourself.
- Yes.

167
00:06:26,428 --> 00:06:28,972
Is the Booker Prize your favorite?

168
00:06:30,599 --> 00:06:32,851
- - Actually, to be honest,
- Yes?

169
00:06:32,935 --> 00:06:36,188
I think my life
can be divided into two parts.

170
00:06:36,271 --> 00:06:38,941
It's after I won
Munhakdongne's New Author Award

171
00:06:39,024 --> 00:06:41,693
and before I won it.

172
00:06:41,777 --> 00:06:44,863
Before that, I was someone
who just wrote by myself.

173
00:06:44,947 --> 00:06:46,740
But after that,

174
00:06:46,823 --> 00:06:49,243
- - I was recognized as an author.
- Yes.

175
00:06:49,326 --> 00:06:51,828
- - You were officially recognized.
- So nothing could compare to

176
00:06:51,912 --> 00:06:54,248
the joy of winning that award.

177
00:06:54,331 --> 00:06:56,875
Personally, I have a favorite award.

178
00:06:56,959 --> 00:06:57,918
The Grand Prize you won?

179
00:06:58,001 --> 00:06:59,628
- - No, not that.
- Okay.

180
00:06:59,878 --> 00:07:02,422
When I work hard,

181
00:07:02,756 --> 00:07:04,967
the viewers give me

182
00:07:05,050 --> 00:07:07,678
- - the "Always Award." That's my favorite.
- I see.

183
00:07:09,763 --> 00:07:11,515
I hope you keep winning it.

184
00:07:11,598 --> 00:07:13,141
- - Always?
- Always.

185
00:07:14,601 --> 00:07:17,312
- - I always want to be loved.
- I see.

186
00:07:17,479 --> 00:07:20,148
- - I enjoyed reading the book,
- Yes.

187
00:07:20,232 --> 00:07:22,693
- - and I loved the film and the series.
- Yes.

188
00:07:22,776 --> 00:07:24,987
But I didn't like your essay.

189
00:07:25,070 --> 00:07:26,488
- - It made me sad.
- Why?

190
00:07:26,864 --> 00:07:28,991
It was called
<i>I Better Not Eat Before Bed Tonight.</i>

191
00:07:29,825 --> 00:07:32,494
Well, it's hard to fall asleep
on an empty stomach.

192
00:07:32,578 --> 00:07:34,079
I couldn't agree more.

193
00:07:35,163 --> 00:07:36,623
I completely agree.

194
00:07:36,707 --> 00:07:38,083
I can't sleep at night.

195
00:07:38,166 --> 00:07:40,919
- - I like to say "FBSE."
- Right.

196
00:07:41,003 --> 00:07:42,671
- - "Full Belly, Sleep Easy."
- Yes.

197
00:07:42,754 --> 00:07:47,301
It's true. No sleeping pill
is more effective than a food coma.

198
00:07:47,384 --> 00:07:50,012
When you eat a lot of carbs and lie down,

199
00:07:50,179 --> 00:07:53,640
it makes you feel peaceful and relaxed

200
00:07:53,724 --> 00:07:56,059
in a way no sleeping pill can.

201
00:07:56,143 --> 00:07:57,728
- - We're not encouraging this.
- Of course.

202
00:07:57,811 --> 00:08:00,230
I even wrote a book called
<i>I Better Not Eat Before Bed Tonight.</i>

203
00:08:00,314 --> 00:08:01,565
READ TO SEE IF HE DID DO AS THE TITLE SAYS

204
00:08:01,648 --> 00:08:03,734
- - Of course, I don't encourage it.
- Yes.

205
00:08:03,817 --> 00:08:06,445
So, you're a well-known author.

206
00:08:06,987 --> 00:08:09,198
When you have a new book out,

207
00:08:09,281 --> 00:08:11,909
do you go to the bookshop
to see if it's doing well?

208
00:08:12,618 --> 00:08:13,577
I'd like to know.

209
00:08:13,827 --> 00:08:16,079
- - A lot of people would be curious.
- Right.

210
00:08:16,163 --> 00:08:17,998
I think most authors

211
00:08:18,081 --> 00:08:19,875
go and check at least once.

212
00:08:19,958 --> 00:08:22,544
Somewhere like Kyobo Book Center
in Gwaghwamun.

213
00:08:22,628 --> 00:08:24,254
- - Rightfully so.
- Right?

214
00:08:24,338 --> 00:08:27,299
It's not even blood, sweat, and tears
that go into it.

215
00:08:27,382 --> 00:08:29,009
- - It's blood and pus.
- Exactly.

216
00:08:29,092 --> 00:08:31,512
There's pain like you're squeezing out pus

217
00:08:31,595 --> 00:08:33,138
- - Right.
- behind every sentence.

218
00:08:33,222 --> 00:08:34,723
You're absolutely right.

219
00:08:34,806 --> 00:08:37,059
Some people lose teeth while writing.

220
00:08:37,142 --> 00:08:40,062
When Kim Hoon
was writing <i>Song of the Sword</i>,

221
00:08:40,145 --> 00:08:43,899
he spat out a molar into the trash can
after he wrote the fourth chapter.

222
00:08:44,024 --> 00:08:46,485
He was so worn out that a tooth fell out.

223
00:08:47,361 --> 00:08:49,404
He probably had gum problems already.

224
00:08:49,613 --> 00:08:52,032
I'm sure he'd been suffering before that.

225
00:08:52,282 --> 00:08:53,867
But writing is also that hard.

226
00:08:53,951 --> 00:08:56,411
It's hard work writing
and publishing a book.

227
00:08:56,495 --> 00:08:59,581
He literally gave it his all.

228
00:08:59,665 --> 00:09:02,543
He was clenching his teeth
from trying so hard

229
00:09:02,668 --> 00:09:04,127
that a tooth fell out.

230
00:09:04,211 --> 00:09:05,796
- - I think so.
- He was bleeding.

231
00:09:05,879 --> 00:09:07,089
- - I think so.
- Yes.

232
00:09:07,172 --> 00:09:09,299
- - That's how a work of art is born.
- Right.

233
00:09:09,383 --> 00:09:11,593
- - That's why you'd want to know
- Yes.

234
00:09:11,677 --> 00:09:13,804
- - if people like it
- Yes.

235
00:09:13,887 --> 00:09:16,014
- - or if it's being overlooked.
- That's true.

236
00:09:16,098 --> 00:09:17,599
- - Of course, I'd like to know.
- Right.

237
00:09:17,683 --> 00:09:19,309
So, you're at the bookshop

238
00:09:19,393 --> 00:09:21,979
and you don't like
where your book is placed.

239
00:09:22,062 --> 00:09:23,272
Have you ever taken it

240
00:09:23,355 --> 00:09:25,691
and put it where more people will see it?

241
00:09:26,358 --> 00:09:27,818
Sneakily and subtly.

242
00:09:27,901 --> 00:09:29,194
Honestly, I have.

243
00:09:29,611 --> 00:09:31,488
WE HAD A FEELING HE'D SAY THAT

244
00:09:31,572 --> 00:09:32,948
I don't do that these days.

245
00:09:33,323 --> 00:09:34,658
I did when I was younger.

246
00:09:35,284 --> 00:09:37,035
- - Anyone would want to.
- Yes.

247
00:09:37,119 --> 00:09:40,831
<i>The books that are</i>
<i>on what we call the display table</i>

248
00:09:40,914 --> 00:09:41,999
<i>are the selected few</i>

249
00:09:42,082 --> 00:09:46,044
among many, many other books.

250
00:09:46,128 --> 00:09:48,422
Most books get put
in the new arrivals section

251
00:09:48,505 --> 00:09:50,591
<i>and then the shelves</i>
<i>before they disappear.</i>

252
00:09:50,674 --> 00:09:53,385
<i>This all happens</i>
<i>within a couple of months.</i>

253
00:09:53,468 --> 00:09:56,763
This even happens to books by
authors who've been around for decades.

254
00:09:56,889 --> 00:09:58,932
For example, I'd take it from the shelf

255
00:09:59,016 --> 00:10:00,309
and put it on the table.

256
00:10:02,019 --> 00:10:04,396
I'd drop it in the bestsellers section.

257
00:10:04,479 --> 00:10:05,606
I wouldn't put it there,

258
00:10:05,689 --> 00:10:06,940
but I'd just drop it there.

259
00:10:07,024 --> 00:10:08,817
Just nudge it a little.

260
00:10:08,901 --> 00:10:10,402
I don't know if that helped

261
00:10:10,611 --> 00:10:13,739
or if the bookshop employee
reorganized it right away.

262
00:10:13,822 --> 00:10:15,532
So, if you decided to write,

263
00:10:15,616 --> 00:10:18,660
- - you must have first liked to read.
- Yes.

264
00:10:18,744 --> 00:10:20,287
What's your favorite book?

265
00:10:20,370 --> 00:10:21,747
- - My favorite book?
- Your favorite.

266
00:10:21,914 --> 00:10:24,166
I have too many to choose from.

267
00:10:24,541 --> 00:10:26,502
But I just happened to bring them today.

268
00:10:28,712 --> 00:10:29,796
Wait a second.

269
00:10:29,880 --> 00:10:31,673
- - This is what I'm picking up today.
- Yes?

270
00:10:31,757 --> 00:10:34,384
You have a lot to say,
a lot of favorite books...

271
00:10:34,468 --> 00:10:35,636
I have a lot of everything.

272
00:10:35,719 --> 00:10:38,013
A lot of fat, problems, and things to say.

273
00:10:38,680 --> 00:10:41,141
- - Hair, too.
- I have a lot of hair.

274
00:10:41,391 --> 00:10:44,102
I'd show you if I could.

275
00:10:44,186 --> 00:10:45,938
I will when we have a chance.

276
00:10:46,021 --> 00:10:47,397
- - The book--
- What chance?

277
00:10:47,481 --> 00:10:48,982
I'm not sure.

278
00:10:49,107 --> 00:10:50,692
There might be a chance at some point.

279
00:10:50,776 --> 00:10:52,152
- - You don't have to.
- Okay.

280
00:10:52,236 --> 00:10:53,195
All right, then.

281
00:10:53,779 --> 00:10:54,947
You don't have to show me.

282
00:10:55,030 --> 00:10:56,823
Goodness. I didn't mean it, anyway.

283
00:10:57,991 --> 00:10:59,910
Do you want to do <i>ssireum,</i>
traditional Korean wrestling, with me?

284
00:10:59,993 --> 00:11:01,411
Oh, I wouldn't dare.

285
00:11:01,537 --> 00:11:03,580
You don't want to kill anyone, do you?

286
00:11:03,664 --> 00:11:04,623
That'd be brutal.

287
00:11:04,706 --> 00:11:06,416
I'll do it with you some other time.

288
00:11:06,917 --> 00:11:08,043
No, you don't have to.

289
00:11:09,086 --> 00:11:10,170
No, thank you.

290
00:11:10,254 --> 00:11:11,213
THEY'LL BE FINE WITHOUT IT

291
00:11:11,505 --> 00:11:13,590
My middle school had a <i>ssireum</i> team.

292
00:11:13,674 --> 00:11:15,008
- - I just remembered.
- Really?

293
00:11:15,092 --> 00:11:17,135
Why didn't anyone ask you to join?

294
00:11:17,219 --> 00:11:19,471
What made you think that?
Of course, they asked.

295
00:11:19,638 --> 00:11:20,764
HA HA

296
00:11:20,848 --> 00:11:24,059
Also, in college, the rugby team
really wanted me.

297
00:11:24,560 --> 00:11:25,811
You'd be great on TV shows.

298
00:11:25,894 --> 00:11:28,063
I told you, I was on five!

299
00:11:28,146 --> 00:11:28,981
HA HA

300
00:11:29,064 --> 00:11:30,816
HE KEEPS BEING RUDE TO HIS GUEST
I already told you about that.

301
00:11:31,441 --> 00:11:33,110
Can I please take my book out?

302
00:11:34,111 --> 00:11:35,445
You're so funny.

303
00:11:35,529 --> 00:11:37,656
- - Here are my favorite books.
- So funny.

304
00:11:38,740 --> 00:11:41,702
It was hard,
but I narrowed it down to these three.

305
00:11:41,785 --> 00:11:46,164
First, Shin Kyung-sook's novel,
<i>The Girl Who Wrote Loneliness</i>.

306
00:11:46,248 --> 00:11:47,583
- - Right.
- This book

307
00:11:47,666 --> 00:11:50,836
is about a girl
who moves from Jeongeup to Seoul

308
00:11:50,919 --> 00:11:52,629
in the '60s to '70s

309
00:11:52,713 --> 00:11:55,924
and attends a work-study program.

310
00:11:56,008 --> 00:11:57,718
She works in a factory during the day

311
00:11:57,801 --> 00:12:01,054
and goes to night school to study.

312
00:12:01,138 --> 00:12:02,347
- - That's what it's about.
- That sounds exhausting.

313
00:12:02,431 --> 00:12:03,765
That's right.

314
00:12:03,849 --> 00:12:06,727
She's so young.
She's only in middle school.

315
00:12:06,810 --> 00:12:08,770
It explores the inner world

316
00:12:08,854 --> 00:12:11,315
and the beauty of the teenage girl.

317
00:12:11,398 --> 00:12:13,942
The next one is <i>A Very Old Joke</i>.

318
00:12:14,026 --> 00:12:15,485
You know Park Wan-suh, right?

319
00:12:15,569 --> 00:12:17,321
- Yes.
- Yes, who wouldn't?

320
00:12:17,404 --> 00:12:20,240
This is by Park Wan-suh,
the author of our generation.

321
00:12:20,324 --> 00:12:24,828
It's about a man who has an affair
with a rich former classmate.

322
00:12:24,912 --> 00:12:26,330
What a bold theme.

323
00:12:26,413 --> 00:12:28,165
Yes, I love this book.

324
00:12:29,124 --> 00:12:31,877
- - I love these kinds of stories.
- I see.

325
00:12:31,960 --> 00:12:33,504
So, I brought this.

326
00:12:33,587 --> 00:12:35,422
And the last one

327
00:12:35,506 --> 00:12:37,049
is by Agatha Christie.

328
00:12:37,132 --> 00:12:40,761
She's a very well-known
English mystery novelist.

329
00:12:40,844 --> 00:12:46,058
I read all 80 of Agatha Christie's books,

330
00:12:46,141 --> 00:12:48,143
and this one's my favorite.

331
00:12:48,227 --> 00:12:50,437
It's called <i>Crooked House</i>.

332
00:12:50,521 --> 00:12:51,688
- I see.
- Yes.

333
00:12:51,772 --> 00:12:54,566
People keep getting murdered

334
00:12:54,650 --> 00:12:56,735
- in this family.
- Right.

335
00:12:56,818 --> 00:12:59,530
So the girl, who's the main character
and the narrator,

336
00:12:59,613 --> 00:13:01,949
tracks down who the murderer is.

337
00:13:02,032 --> 00:13:03,951
Among all of Agatha Christie's books,

338
00:13:04,034 --> 00:13:06,370
- - That's right.
- this one's your favorite.

339
00:13:06,453 --> 00:13:08,497
I think it's the essence of her work.

340
00:13:10,791 --> 00:13:12,668
I, Hocrates, the man who asks,

341
00:13:13,126 --> 00:13:17,548
will start asking questions
about Park Sang-young's life.

342
00:13:17,923 --> 00:13:20,592
<i>The first chapter</i>
<i>of Park Sang-young's life.</i>

343
00:13:20,676 --> 00:13:22,094
<i>Crooked House</i>.

344
00:13:23,136 --> 00:13:26,181
"I made that story up."

345
00:13:26,265 --> 00:13:28,267
"I don't believe that."

346
00:13:28,517 --> 00:13:30,269
"But it's true."

347
00:13:30,352 --> 00:13:34,147
"I sometimes make up stories. It's fun."

348
00:13:34,231 --> 00:13:35,399
FROM <i>CROOKED HOUSE</i>

349
00:13:35,774 --> 00:13:38,777
Since you were a kid,

350
00:13:38,861 --> 00:13:42,531
have you liked to come up with stories?

351
00:13:42,614 --> 00:13:44,408
I loved it.

352
00:13:44,491 --> 00:13:46,535
It was like this.

353
00:13:46,618 --> 00:13:50,038
<i>When my parents' friends would come over,</i>

354
00:13:50,122 --> 00:13:53,000
<i>they'd always talk to me.</i>

355
00:13:53,083 --> 00:13:54,501
<i>They liked the way I talked.</i>

356
00:13:54,585 --> 00:13:57,087
- <i>- They did?</i>
<i>- They thought I was fun to listen to.</i>

357
00:13:57,171 --> 00:13:58,964
<i>And I was also a good listener.</i>

358
00:13:59,047 --> 00:14:00,757
<i>So they liked talking to me.</i>

359
00:14:00,841 --> 00:14:03,093
When I'd go to after-school classes,

360
00:14:03,177 --> 00:14:05,554
the teachers said I talked like an adult.

361
00:14:05,637 --> 00:14:08,098
- - I got that a lot.
- I see.

362
00:14:08,182 --> 00:14:10,434
I think that shows

363
00:14:10,517 --> 00:14:15,647
that I've had this talent or personality
ever since I was a kid.

364
00:14:15,731 --> 00:14:18,442
So, this full-length novel

365
00:14:18,525 --> 00:14:20,194
made young Sang-young

366
00:14:20,277 --> 00:14:21,987
- - like books?
- Yes.

367
00:14:22,070 --> 00:14:25,240
I first read Agatha Christie's books...

368
00:14:25,324 --> 00:14:27,326
Do you remember
the Asian financial crisis?

369
00:14:27,409 --> 00:14:28,619
- - Of course.
- Yes.

370
00:14:28,702 --> 00:14:31,371
It's a big event that affected

371
00:14:31,455 --> 00:14:33,582
- - most Korean citizens
- Yes.

372
00:14:33,665 --> 00:14:35,125
around 1997 and 1998.

373
00:14:35,417 --> 00:14:38,253
- - I was in elementary school at the time.
- Right.

374
00:14:38,337 --> 00:14:40,797
You know those asset seizure stickers?

375
00:14:40,881 --> 00:14:43,300
I was home alone one day

376
00:14:43,634 --> 00:14:45,886
when I heard the doorbell
and opened the door.

377
00:14:45,969 --> 00:14:49,014
Then, people in suits came in
without taking their shoes off.

378
00:14:49,097 --> 00:14:51,183
More than a dozen of them came in

379
00:14:51,266 --> 00:14:52,976
and put those stickers everywhere.

380
00:14:53,060 --> 00:14:54,770
I was only a pre-teen.

381
00:14:54,853 --> 00:14:56,355
Imagine how scary that was.

382
00:14:56,438 --> 00:14:57,731
- - Were you alone?
- Yes.

383
00:14:57,814 --> 00:14:59,233
So, I called my mom.

384
00:14:59,316 --> 00:15:02,277
She came home from work
and started crying.

385
00:15:02,361 --> 00:15:04,696
She said, "I'm sorry you had to see that."

386
00:15:04,780 --> 00:15:06,657
That's when I felt how bad it was.

387
00:15:06,740 --> 00:15:09,993
After that, they asked
my dad's friend's family to babysit me.

388
00:15:10,077 --> 00:15:13,914
They lived in the same apartment complex
as we did.

389
00:15:13,997 --> 00:15:16,375
- - I see.
- They had a lot of daughters.

390
00:15:16,458 --> 00:15:17,793
There were three girls

391
00:15:17,876 --> 00:15:20,587
who were in middle school and high school.

392
00:15:20,671 --> 00:15:23,298
- - And the youngest had a bookshelf.
- I see.

393
00:15:23,382 --> 00:15:24,633
The bookshelf had

394
00:15:24,716 --> 00:15:27,469
the complete works of Agatha Christie.

395
00:15:27,553 --> 00:15:30,097
I started reading them,
and they were so good.

396
00:15:30,180 --> 00:15:32,015
My world before those books

397
00:15:32,099 --> 00:15:34,726
was limited to world literature
adapted for kids and teens.

398
00:15:34,810 --> 00:15:36,270
- - Books like that.
- Right.

399
00:15:36,353 --> 00:15:39,022
It was a somewhat sanitized world.

400
00:15:39,314 --> 00:15:42,025
But in Agatha Christie's world,

401
00:15:42,109 --> 00:15:44,069
there was adultery, passionate affairs,

402
00:15:44,152 --> 00:15:46,071
murder, crime, and violence all over.

403
00:15:46,280 --> 00:15:48,532
They were so shocking
and stimulating to me.

404
00:15:48,907 --> 00:15:51,618
Those books were so thrilling.

405
00:15:51,702 --> 00:15:53,495
Reading books

406
00:15:53,704 --> 00:15:56,415
became fun to me.

407
00:15:56,498 --> 00:15:59,376
In just a few months, I read all 80 books.

408
00:15:59,459 --> 00:16:01,086
You were only around ten.

409
00:16:01,170 --> 00:16:02,880
- - It would depend on the child,
- Yes.

410
00:16:02,963 --> 00:16:05,340
but it must've been lonely
to be by yourself.

411
00:16:05,424 --> 00:16:08,510
Also, you must not have liked
being at someone else's place.

412
00:16:08,594 --> 00:16:10,345
My mom was also worried,

413
00:16:10,429 --> 00:16:14,016
and other adults
were concerned about that, too.

414
00:16:14,099 --> 00:16:16,518
But to be honest,
my mom didn't let me watch TV,

415
00:16:16,602 --> 00:16:20,022
but that place had everything I wanted.

416
00:16:20,105 --> 00:16:22,149
- - I could watch you on TV.
- Right.

417
00:16:22,232 --> 00:16:24,234
I could watch <i>Lee So-ra's Propose.</i>

418
00:16:24,318 --> 00:16:26,778
They also had an audio player,

419
00:16:26,862 --> 00:16:29,531
so I could listen to new songs by H.O.T.

420
00:16:29,615 --> 00:16:31,325
and S.E.S., too.

421
00:16:31,408 --> 00:16:34,119
That place was like
an amusement park to me.

422
00:16:34,203 --> 00:16:35,579
Did you like K-pop idols?

423
00:16:35,662 --> 00:16:37,956
I loved them. I still do.

424
00:16:38,373 --> 00:16:41,919
I've liked K-pop idols
for almost 20 years now.

425
00:16:42,002 --> 00:16:43,253
Who did you like first?

426
00:16:43,795 --> 00:16:45,422
I'm sure everyone loved them.

427
00:16:45,506 --> 00:16:48,258
It was S.E.S.

428
00:16:48,342 --> 00:16:51,345
The first album I ever bought in my life

429
00:16:51,428 --> 00:16:53,430
was the first album by S.E.S.

430
00:16:53,514 --> 00:16:55,057
That's when it all started.

431
00:16:55,432 --> 00:16:58,810
So, you've never stopped
being a fan since then?

432
00:16:58,894 --> 00:17:00,479
Yes. I started liking
other groups as well,

433
00:17:00,562 --> 00:17:02,064
but it has never stopped.

434
00:17:02,814 --> 00:17:04,483
Who else do you like?

435
00:17:04,566 --> 00:17:07,027
To list the ones
that I've been really into,

436
00:17:07,110 --> 00:17:09,696
there was TWICE.

437
00:17:09,780 --> 00:17:11,114
I absolutely loved them.

438
00:17:11,448 --> 00:17:14,034
I voted during
their first reality survival show.

439
00:17:14,117 --> 00:17:15,786
I picked those members myself.

440
00:17:16,745 --> 00:17:17,579
FANS WOULD OFTEN SAY
"I RAISED THOSE MEMBERS"

441
00:17:17,663 --> 00:17:19,706
And fast forward to now,

442
00:17:19,873 --> 00:17:21,834
I've been into TWS.

443
00:17:21,917 --> 00:17:23,961
You know, "Plot Twist."

444
00:17:25,003 --> 00:17:26,213
SUDDENLY SHOWING THE MOVES
And "OVERDRIVE."

445
00:17:26,296 --> 00:17:28,090
- - You also like boy groups?
- I do.

446
00:17:28,173 --> 00:17:29,466
I like them equally.

447
00:17:29,550 --> 00:17:31,176
IMAGES HE PROVIDED
<i>Both girl and boy groups.</i>

448
00:17:31,260 --> 00:17:33,262
<i>I love them.</i>

449
00:17:33,345 --> 00:17:35,514
My friends say
I like groups that end with an "S" sound.

450
00:17:35,597 --> 00:17:37,391
S.E.S, TWICE, and TWS.

451
00:17:37,474 --> 00:17:38,892
- - They end with an "S" sound.
- They do.

452
00:17:41,687 --> 00:17:43,856
TWS is from PLEDIS Entertainment.

453
00:17:43,939 --> 00:17:45,858
- - That's right. You know their company?
- PLEDIS.

454
00:17:45,941 --> 00:17:47,109
That's four S's.

455
00:17:47,609 --> 00:17:49,111
You're right!

456
00:17:49,194 --> 00:17:50,487
PLEDIS: TWS'S AGENCY

457
00:17:50,571 --> 00:17:52,197
I'm friends with the founder.

458
00:17:52,281 --> 00:17:53,824
Oh, with Mr. Han Sung-soo?

459
00:17:54,032 --> 00:17:56,952
HOCRATES KNOWS EVERYONE
Could you tell him that I love TWS?

460
00:17:57,035 --> 00:17:59,162
I couldn't get tickets to their fan event.

461
00:17:59,246 --> 00:18:01,039
- - Oh, no!
- I'm so sad about that.

462
00:18:01,123 --> 00:18:03,584
You even know the founder's name.

463
00:18:03,667 --> 00:18:06,128
Trust me, every fan does.

464
00:18:06,211 --> 00:18:07,588
- - They do?
- I know all of them.

465
00:18:07,671 --> 00:18:10,632
Lee Soo-man, Park Jin-young,
Han Sung-soo...

466
00:18:10,716 --> 00:18:11,800
How could I not know them?

467
00:18:12,217 --> 00:18:13,677
Of course, I know them.

468
00:18:13,760 --> 00:18:15,804
Would you like to say something to him?

469
00:18:15,888 --> 00:18:16,889
To Mr. Han Sung-soo?

470
00:18:16,972 --> 00:18:19,516
- - Not to TWS, but to Mr. Han Sung-soo?
- Yes.

471
00:18:19,808 --> 00:18:21,018
Mr. Han.

472
00:18:21,101 --> 00:18:23,854
He's the one who made TWS
into the great group it is today.

473
00:18:23,937 --> 00:18:26,815
That's right. Sir, you have a great eye.

474
00:18:26,940 --> 00:18:28,775
Please, do your best.

475
00:18:29,359 --> 00:18:32,321
Fans have a lot of complaints.

476
00:18:32,738 --> 00:18:35,115
We hope you'll work harder.

477
00:18:35,616 --> 00:18:37,701
WE HOPE THE MESSAGE REACHES HIM

478
00:18:37,784 --> 00:18:39,494
All right.

479
00:18:39,578 --> 00:18:41,788
Sure, you can like books.

480
00:18:41,872 --> 00:18:43,248
You can like books,

481
00:18:43,332 --> 00:18:46,376
but writing
is a different matter, isn't it?

482
00:18:46,835 --> 00:18:48,504
When did you discover your talent?

483
00:18:50,339 --> 00:18:51,632
I wasn't trying to,

484
00:18:51,715 --> 00:18:54,593
but every time
there was a writing contest at school,

485
00:18:54,927 --> 00:18:58,013
I'd win first prize without even trying.

486
00:18:58,430 --> 00:18:59,973
Wasn't it like that for you?

487
00:19:00,057 --> 00:19:02,017
Didn't you just somehow start <i>ssireum?</i>

488
00:19:03,352 --> 00:19:05,979
- - All the chubby kids did it back then.
- I see.

489
00:19:07,773 --> 00:19:08,982
But still,

490
00:19:09,066 --> 00:19:11,026
you were widely recognized,

491
00:19:11,109 --> 00:19:13,237
even if it was for your build.

492
00:19:13,320 --> 00:19:14,655
- - Right.
- I was the same.

493
00:19:14,988 --> 00:19:17,407
I didn't know I was a talented writer,

494
00:19:17,491 --> 00:19:19,201
but I kept getting recognition.

495
00:19:19,284 --> 00:19:21,828
Everyone told me I was a good writer

496
00:19:21,912 --> 00:19:25,666
and that I was well-spoken.

497
00:19:25,958 --> 00:19:29,086
In storytelling contests
or debate competitions,

498
00:19:29,169 --> 00:19:31,213
I won all the prizes.

499
00:19:31,296 --> 00:19:33,048
You weren't trying that hard,

500
00:19:33,131 --> 00:19:34,424
but you won contests.

501
00:19:34,508 --> 00:19:37,636
I never tried my very hardest.

502
00:19:37,719 --> 00:19:42,683
I'd have to say
that was a matter of talent.

503
00:19:42,850 --> 00:19:45,143
Was that too obnoxious?
That wasn't my intent.

504
00:19:45,227 --> 00:19:46,687
No, it's okay.

505
00:19:46,770 --> 00:19:49,189
You're just being honest.

506
00:19:49,273 --> 00:19:51,483
I'm not good at anything but that.

507
00:19:52,901 --> 00:19:56,405
Let's move on to the second chapter
of Park Sang-young's life.

508
00:19:56,488 --> 00:19:58,490
- <i>- The Girl Who Wrote Loneliness.</i>
- Okay.

509
00:19:59,199 --> 00:20:00,158
"Writing.

510
00:20:00,492 --> 00:20:03,370
The reason why I'm so attached to writing

511
00:20:04,037 --> 00:20:08,083
is probably that I think
this is the only way

512
00:20:08,166 --> 00:20:10,836
I can get away from feeling
like I don't matter."

513
00:20:10,919 --> 00:20:11,879
FROM <i>THE GIRL WHO WROTE LONELINESS</i>

514
00:20:12,296 --> 00:20:13,630
Could you explain?

515
00:20:13,714 --> 00:20:16,425
- - I think it's pretty straightforward.
- Right.

516
00:20:16,508 --> 00:20:20,512
She's a teenage girl who suddenly ends up
in the unfamiliar city of Seoul.

517
00:20:20,804 --> 00:20:23,849
- - The book is about her loneliness.
- Yes.

518
00:20:23,932 --> 00:20:28,562
The thing that gave meaning
to her life was writing.

519
00:20:28,645 --> 00:20:31,064
That's what the section is talking about.

520
00:20:31,440 --> 00:20:34,693
Because I'm also an author,

521
00:20:34,776 --> 00:20:36,445
that phrase really spoke to me.

522
00:20:36,528 --> 00:20:39,865
How did this book
influence you as an author?

523
00:20:39,948 --> 00:20:41,491
THE INFLUENCE OF
<i>THE GIRL WHO WROTE LONELINESS</i>

524
00:20:41,575 --> 00:20:45,162
Because of the situations
that I mentioned before,

525
00:20:45,245 --> 00:20:47,998
I lived in Daegu
until I graduated high school.

526
00:20:48,081 --> 00:20:49,416
- - Yes.
- During that time,

527
00:20:49,833 --> 00:20:51,460
I was very frustrated.

528
00:20:51,543 --> 00:20:53,712
I wanted to be free.

529
00:20:54,296 --> 00:20:55,589
I wanted to break free.

530
00:20:55,672 --> 00:20:59,051
That's why,
when I was applying to college,

531
00:20:59,134 --> 00:21:02,763
I applied to every single university
in the city of Seoul.

532
00:21:03,138 --> 00:21:05,641
So, I had to go take the tests.

533
00:21:06,141 --> 00:21:07,434
But there was a problem.

534
00:21:08,185 --> 00:21:10,854
The train tickets
from Daegu to Seoul were expensive.

535
00:21:10,938 --> 00:21:13,482
I had to get round-trip tickets.

536
00:21:13,690 --> 00:21:15,400
I applied to ten universities,

537
00:21:15,484 --> 00:21:18,278
which means the tickets
would cost a million won in total.

538
00:21:18,570 --> 00:21:20,489
My mom thought it made no sense.

539
00:21:20,572 --> 00:21:23,367
Trains, accommodation,
and application fees are no joke.

540
00:21:23,450 --> 00:21:26,662
So she came up with the idea
of me staying in Seoul

541
00:21:26,995 --> 00:21:29,873
and coming back
after I've taken all the tests.

542
00:21:29,957 --> 00:21:32,835
So I stayed with my cousin
in his boarding house room.

543
00:21:32,918 --> 00:21:35,796
I stayed in that room in Seoul

544
00:21:35,879 --> 00:21:38,257
over the summer break.

545
00:21:38,799 --> 00:21:41,593
I was there by myself,

546
00:21:41,677 --> 00:21:43,762
taking essay tests and entry exams.

547
00:21:43,846 --> 00:21:46,765
I couldn't talk to anyone,
so I was lonely.

548
00:21:47,307 --> 00:21:49,685
I read this book in that situation,

549
00:21:50,018 --> 00:21:51,979
and every phrase

550
00:21:52,062 --> 00:21:55,732
describing the girl's loneliness
and sense of isolation

551
00:21:55,816 --> 00:21:57,359
resonated with me.

552
00:21:57,442 --> 00:22:00,988
It brought me great comfort.

553
00:22:01,321 --> 00:22:03,907
It felt like someone else
was voicing for me

554
00:22:03,991 --> 00:22:06,326
the loneliness
that I couldn't put into words.

555
00:22:06,827 --> 00:22:10,873
It felt like someone
had entered my heart and then left.

556
00:22:11,373 --> 00:22:13,208
So naturally, I started thinking,

557
00:22:13,750 --> 00:22:15,419
"If an author is someone

558
00:22:15,502 --> 00:22:18,297
who can affect other people's lives

559
00:22:18,380 --> 00:22:20,507
so deeply,

560
00:22:20,591 --> 00:22:23,635
it'd be meaningful
to devote my life to being one."

561
00:22:24,261 --> 00:22:26,722
I thought it could be a noble thing

562
00:22:26,805 --> 00:22:28,724
for the first time in my life.

563
00:22:29,057 --> 00:22:31,393
After I read
<i>The Girl Who Wrote Loneliness</i>,

564
00:22:31,727 --> 00:22:34,980
I genuinely started considering
becoming an author.

565
00:22:35,063 --> 00:22:37,399
It motivated me.

566
00:22:39,735 --> 00:22:41,570
I want to ask you something.

567
00:22:41,653 --> 00:22:43,989
Listening to your family and colleagues

568
00:22:44,072 --> 00:22:47,576
cheering you on during hard times...

569
00:22:48,368 --> 00:22:51,663
You don't find comfort in it at the time.

570
00:22:51,747 --> 00:22:54,082
But reading sad novels

571
00:22:54,166 --> 00:22:57,878
gives you courage, comfort,
and the power to get back up.

572
00:22:58,045 --> 00:23:00,005
Why do you think this happens?

573
00:23:00,088 --> 00:23:01,673
- - Well...
- Isn't it a bit selfish?

574
00:23:01,757 --> 00:23:03,300
It is,

575
00:23:03,634 --> 00:23:06,136
but novels are a selfish genre.

576
00:23:06,220 --> 00:23:09,097
And humans are naturally selfish,
if you think about it.

577
00:23:09,473 --> 00:23:12,059
That's why I think

578
00:23:12,142 --> 00:23:16,480
it's natural
that reading can do that for you.

579
00:23:16,563 --> 00:23:19,399
That just means you read it right.

580
00:23:21,068 --> 00:23:23,111
After enduring that period,

581
00:23:23,195 --> 00:23:25,822
- - you finally went on to college.
- Yes.

582
00:23:26,198 --> 00:23:29,785
Did you major in creative writing
or Korean language and literature?

583
00:23:30,452 --> 00:23:33,539
- - I wanted to major in either of those.
- Yes.

584
00:23:33,622 --> 00:23:38,126
But I ended up majoring
in French language and literature.

585
00:23:38,752 --> 00:23:40,003
- - French?
- Yes.

586
00:23:41,255 --> 00:23:43,340
I know a bit of French. <i>Oh mon Dieu!</i>

587
00:23:45,509 --> 00:23:47,594
<i>Bonjour! Avez-vous mangé?</i>

588
00:23:47,678 --> 00:23:49,263
What's that? <i>Avez-vous mangé?</i>

589
00:23:49,346 --> 00:23:50,472
It's "Have you eaten?"

590
00:23:50,556 --> 00:23:52,015
<i>Avez-vous mangé?</i>

591
00:23:52,099 --> 00:23:53,350
How good is your French?

592
00:23:53,433 --> 00:23:55,310
I can't even read store signs.

593
00:23:56,019 --> 00:23:59,231
I gave up on the French language.

594
00:23:59,314 --> 00:24:02,651
I focused on the literature part instead.

595
00:24:02,734 --> 00:24:04,778
I kind of neglected my studies,

596
00:24:04,862 --> 00:24:08,198
- - but I double-majored in journalism,
- I see.

597
00:24:08,282 --> 00:24:11,118
<i>and attended academies</i>

598
00:24:11,201 --> 00:24:13,078
<i>because I really wanted to write.</i>

599
00:24:13,745 --> 00:24:16,456
I kept writing stories in secret

600
00:24:16,540 --> 00:24:18,083
and submitted them

601
00:24:18,166 --> 00:24:19,751
to different literary contests.

602
00:24:20,210 --> 00:24:23,130
That's how I grew
my dream of becoming an author.

603
00:24:23,213 --> 00:24:26,550
But actually, being a full-time author

604
00:24:26,884 --> 00:24:29,845
comes with a lot of difficulties, right?

605
00:24:29,928 --> 00:24:31,805
- - Yes, a lot of difficulties.
- Right.

606
00:24:32,055 --> 00:24:33,432
Getting a book published

607
00:24:33,515 --> 00:24:35,517
isn't as important
as getting people to read it.

608
00:24:36,185 --> 00:24:37,895
I wanted to write for a living,

609
00:24:37,978 --> 00:24:41,231
so I started working for a magazine.

610
00:24:41,315 --> 00:24:43,025
- - You started working.
- Yes.

611
00:24:43,108 --> 00:24:45,068
- - That's the reality.
- Of course.

612
00:24:45,152 --> 00:24:48,197
As I mentioned before,
my family wasn't wealthy.

613
00:24:48,280 --> 00:24:49,907
I had student loans.

614
00:24:49,990 --> 00:24:51,617
It was an apprenticeship.

615
00:24:51,700 --> 00:24:53,452
- - There was a mentor-mentee culture.
- I see.

616
00:24:53,535 --> 00:24:57,289
The mentor trained interns on the job,

617
00:24:57,372 --> 00:24:59,374
and I was an intern reporter.

618
00:24:59,791 --> 00:25:04,087
I was bullied at work, so to speak.

619
00:25:04,213 --> 00:25:07,049
Getting coffee for the seniors

620
00:25:07,132 --> 00:25:08,675
was a given at the time.

621
00:25:08,759 --> 00:25:12,012
But aside from that, there were also
personal attacks and insults.

622
00:25:12,095 --> 00:25:13,639
I was born in 1988.

623
00:25:13,722 --> 00:25:16,308
One of the interns was also born in 1988.

624
00:25:16,391 --> 00:25:19,645
We must've been
around 25 or 26 at the time.

625
00:25:20,103 --> 00:25:23,065
The seniors were
watching us work and said,

626
00:25:23,398 --> 00:25:27,361
"Was there a nuclear accident in 1988?
These kids are the worst."

627
00:25:27,444 --> 00:25:29,112
Something like that.

628
00:25:29,196 --> 00:25:32,533
I thought that was harsh,

629
00:25:32,616 --> 00:25:34,117
but I also found it funny.

630
00:25:34,201 --> 00:25:36,662
It went like that every day.

631
00:25:37,079 --> 00:25:40,749
I came to work at 9 a.m.
and left at 11 p.m.

632
00:25:40,832 --> 00:25:42,459
I worked every weekend.

633
00:25:42,543 --> 00:25:44,586
But I only earned

634
00:25:44,878 --> 00:25:48,590
around 1.08 million won
per month after taxes.

635
00:25:48,674 --> 00:25:50,551
After paying rent and so on,

636
00:25:50,634 --> 00:25:53,595
I would be left with nothing.

637
00:25:54,137 --> 00:25:56,723
So those were difficult times.

638
00:25:58,141 --> 00:25:59,560
What was hardest for me

639
00:25:59,643 --> 00:26:02,896
was that I started working there to write,

640
00:26:02,980 --> 00:26:05,607
but I was only copying the press releases.

641
00:26:05,691 --> 00:26:08,068
- - Right.
- That was my job.

642
00:26:08,151 --> 00:26:10,904
I had stories inside of me

643
00:26:10,988 --> 00:26:13,866
that I wanted to tell
using my own language.

644
00:26:14,491 --> 00:26:16,910
But all I was doing
was writing for someone else.

645
00:26:16,994 --> 00:26:20,455
That wasn't the direction I wanted to go.
It wasn't the life I wanted.

646
00:26:20,539 --> 00:26:22,708
I had a strong feeling that it wasn't.

647
00:26:23,625 --> 00:26:25,460
That's why I thought,

648
00:26:26,003 --> 00:26:28,297
"Screw it, I'm still in my twenties.

649
00:26:28,380 --> 00:26:32,551
I'm already in debt.
What's a little more?"

650
00:26:32,676 --> 00:26:34,636
I went to creative writing grad school

651
00:26:34,720 --> 00:26:37,055
to write whatever I wanted.

652
00:26:37,139 --> 00:26:39,016
That's what I decided to do.

653
00:26:39,099 --> 00:26:40,434
So you quit your job?

654
00:26:40,517 --> 00:26:42,519
Yes, I just left,

655
00:26:42,603 --> 00:26:44,438
went to grad school,

656
00:26:44,646 --> 00:26:45,939
and started writing.

657
00:26:46,023 --> 00:26:49,610
I wrote a twelve-page short story
every week.

658
00:26:49,860 --> 00:26:52,946
In my first semester,
I submitted one to a writing contest

659
00:26:53,488 --> 00:26:54,990
and made it to the finals.

660
00:26:55,365 --> 00:26:56,950
I came in second.

661
00:26:57,034 --> 00:26:58,535
You're often one of the finalists.

662
00:26:58,619 --> 00:27:00,454
That's my specialty.

663
00:27:00,537 --> 00:27:01,747
AUTHOR WHO ALWAYS GETS NOMINATED

664
00:27:01,830 --> 00:27:03,498
"Your specialty."

665
00:27:03,999 --> 00:27:05,667
It's quite a shame,

666
00:27:05,751 --> 00:27:07,711
but do often end up
being one of the finalists.

667
00:27:08,170 --> 00:27:09,796
Don't be like that.

668
00:27:09,880 --> 00:27:12,591
Hold on. I'll tell you why it's true.

669
00:27:12,925 --> 00:27:16,428
I made it to second place on my first try.

670
00:27:16,512 --> 00:27:19,181
I thought if I tried a couple more times,

671
00:27:19,264 --> 00:27:21,433
I would win first place.

672
00:27:21,934 --> 00:27:24,102
So I made an ultimatum.

673
00:27:24,186 --> 00:27:27,356
I thought, if I couldn't
become an author in two years,

674
00:27:27,439 --> 00:27:30,400
I'd give up completely
and try to make a living

675
00:27:30,484 --> 00:27:32,945
- - doing whatever I could.
- Right.

676
00:27:33,028 --> 00:27:34,821
May I add something?

677
00:27:35,113 --> 00:27:38,492
I was training as an athlete
at a similar point in time,

678
00:27:38,575 --> 00:27:41,578
and I think
that's the period that drives you crazy,

679
00:27:42,204 --> 00:27:44,540
- - when it's just out of reach.
- Exactly.

680
00:27:44,623 --> 00:27:46,250
- - If there's no chance of winning, fine.
- Right.

681
00:27:46,333 --> 00:27:47,793
But if you reach the finals and lose...

682
00:27:47,876 --> 00:27:49,711
- - It's maddening.
- You can't even quit.

683
00:27:49,795 --> 00:27:51,880
In those two years,

684
00:27:51,964 --> 00:27:55,133
I kept submitting to contests
and counted the times.

685
00:27:55,217 --> 00:27:57,469
It was 50 times.

686
00:27:57,553 --> 00:28:00,138
Almost every time,
I lost in the final round.

687
00:28:00,514 --> 00:28:01,974
In the final round?

688
00:28:02,307 --> 00:28:05,602
Not every time,
but I made it to the finals so many times.

689
00:28:05,686 --> 00:28:07,104
You really are a finalist,
through and through.

690
00:28:07,187 --> 00:28:08,856
That's what I really was.

691
00:28:08,939 --> 00:28:14,111
I still remember the names of the authors
who beat me and won.

692
00:28:14,194 --> 00:28:16,029
Even after over a decade,

693
00:28:16,154 --> 00:28:17,823
I can still give you ten names.

694
00:28:17,906 --> 00:28:19,992
Park Seo-lyeon, Jung Young-su, Kim Mella,

695
00:28:20,075 --> 00:28:22,411
Yang Seon-hyeong, and so on.

696
00:28:22,494 --> 00:28:25,080
I heard this story from your perspective,

697
00:28:25,163 --> 00:28:27,457
but I bet the judges
couldn't believe it either.

698
00:28:27,541 --> 00:28:28,500
I'm sure of it.

699
00:28:28,584 --> 00:28:30,502
"He was just eliminated.
Did he submit again?"

700
00:28:31,044 --> 00:28:32,546
It was really like that.

701
00:28:32,629 --> 00:28:34,965
"Did you submit the same story
in a different contest?"

702
00:28:35,048 --> 00:28:36,091
AN URBAN LEGEND AMONG WRITING CONTESTS

703
00:28:36,466 --> 00:28:37,926
Then, my two years were up.

704
00:28:38,010 --> 00:28:40,262
After I graduated,

705
00:28:40,345 --> 00:28:42,306
all I had was a debt of 20 million won

706
00:28:42,389 --> 00:28:44,474
and the memory of failing 50 times.

707
00:28:44,558 --> 00:28:46,268
That was all I was left with.

708
00:28:46,351 --> 00:28:48,437
- - You probably wanted to give up.
- Yes.

709
00:28:48,520 --> 00:28:50,022
I really did.

710
00:28:50,689 --> 00:28:52,191
So I started working again.

711
00:28:52,274 --> 00:28:54,318
- - Again?
- Yes, but this time,

712
00:28:54,401 --> 00:28:56,486
I put on a suit

713
00:28:56,570 --> 00:28:58,739
and went to an office.

714
00:28:58,822 --> 00:29:01,241
- - It was just an ordinary company.
- I see.

715
00:29:01,325 --> 00:29:03,619
- - So you gave up on writing.
- Yes.

716
00:29:03,702 --> 00:29:06,788
But every night in bed,

717
00:29:06,914 --> 00:29:09,625
I felt uncomfortable somewhere down there.

718
00:29:10,417 --> 00:29:12,336
I tried to figure out why.

719
00:29:12,419 --> 00:29:14,213
It turns out I couldn't give it up.

720
00:29:14,838 --> 00:29:16,173
I wanted to write.

721
00:29:16,256 --> 00:29:18,550
But I didn't have time because of work.

722
00:29:18,634 --> 00:29:19,885
I thought about it.

723
00:29:19,968 --> 00:29:22,429
If I went to bed
around midnight or 1 a.m.,

724
00:29:22,513 --> 00:29:24,640
I always woke up around 5 a.m.

725
00:29:24,723 --> 00:29:27,017
I'd keep my eyes closed and wait

726
00:29:27,100 --> 00:29:29,144
until the morning before going to work.

727
00:29:29,228 --> 00:29:30,646
I decided to use that.

728
00:29:30,729 --> 00:29:31,813
- - So...
- How?

729
00:29:31,897 --> 00:29:33,774
- - When I woke up at 5 a.m.,
- Yes.

730
00:29:33,857 --> 00:29:35,984
I'd get up, take a shower,

731
00:29:36,068 --> 00:29:38,028
go to the office,

732
00:29:38,111 --> 00:29:42,032
and write at the coffee shop
on the first floor.

733
00:29:42,157 --> 00:29:43,367
If work started at nine,

734
00:29:43,450 --> 00:29:45,244
that means you had three hours.

735
00:29:45,327 --> 00:29:46,954
Yes, I started at six

736
00:29:47,412 --> 00:29:49,873
and wrote until 8:57 a.m.

737
00:29:49,957 --> 00:29:52,876
before I ran up the stairs to work.

738
00:29:53,293 --> 00:29:58,131
I wrote every morning like that
from January to June.

739
00:29:58,632 --> 00:30:00,759
So I wrote for six months

740
00:30:00,843 --> 00:30:03,929
and submitted
to the Munhakdongne contest in June.

741
00:30:04,012 --> 00:30:07,432
On the day the winner would be announced,
I took a day off. I was at Seoul Station.

742
00:30:07,516 --> 00:30:09,101
Okay, why?

743
00:30:09,184 --> 00:30:11,520
My mom was coming to Seoul

744
00:30:11,603 --> 00:30:13,146
- - for her physical examination.
- Okay.

745
00:30:13,230 --> 00:30:16,275
So I was waiting for her
in the McDonald's at Seoul Station.

746
00:30:16,817 --> 00:30:19,278
And I got a call
from a number starting with 031.

747
00:30:19,611 --> 00:30:21,697
When I saw that, I got a feeling.

748
00:30:21,780 --> 00:30:23,907
- - Right.
- I could feel it.

749
00:30:23,991 --> 00:30:26,577
I felt chills on the back of my neck.

750
00:30:26,869 --> 00:30:29,413
So I answered, "Hello?"

751
00:30:29,496 --> 00:30:31,206
They said, "This is Munhakdongne,"

752
00:30:31,290 --> 00:30:32,291
and I knew I got it.

753
00:30:32,875 --> 00:30:35,752
I was so happy that tears came to my eyes.

754
00:30:35,836 --> 00:30:37,754
So, I hung up in a rush,

755
00:30:37,838 --> 00:30:39,798
and then I saw my mom.

756
00:30:39,882 --> 00:30:41,592
She came up from the KTX platforms,

757
00:30:41,675 --> 00:30:43,760
and I yelled,
"Mom, I won the Munhakdongne contest!"

758
00:30:43,844 --> 00:30:45,512
She was freaking out and screaming.

759
00:30:45,596 --> 00:30:47,389
Everyone was looking at us.

760
00:30:47,472 --> 00:30:48,807
We were hugging each other.

761
00:30:48,891 --> 00:30:51,351
We were freaking out together.

762
00:30:51,435 --> 00:30:53,812
She wanted me to tell my dad,
so I called him.

763
00:30:54,021 --> 00:30:56,523
I said, "Dad, I won Munhakdongne!
I'm a professional author now!"

764
00:30:56,607 --> 00:30:57,941
He was screaming, too.

765
00:30:58,025 --> 00:30:59,193
He said he was so happy

766
00:30:59,276 --> 00:31:02,529
because he knew how hard I'd been trying.

767
00:31:02,613 --> 00:31:05,115
Then, he asked me if winning
the <i>Dongnebangne</i> contest was a good thing.

768
00:31:06,742 --> 00:31:08,368
I said, "Dad, <i>Dongnebangne</i>

769
00:31:09,244 --> 00:31:13,874
is a free daily newspaper
you can use to buy secondhand goods.

770
00:31:13,957 --> 00:31:16,251
Munhakdongne is a literary magazine
and publisher."

771
00:31:16,335 --> 00:31:18,295
I had to correct him on that.

772
00:31:18,378 --> 00:31:20,130
- - I heard there was a cash prize.
- Yes.

773
00:31:20,214 --> 00:31:22,049
What did you do with the money?

774
00:31:22,132 --> 00:31:24,801
As I mentioned before,
I had a lot of debt.

775
00:31:24,885 --> 00:31:28,138
Munhakdongne's cash prize
was ten million won.

776
00:31:28,222 --> 00:31:30,599
I wanted to pay off a big chunk of my debt

777
00:31:30,682 --> 00:31:32,559
and eat somewhere nice.

778
00:31:32,643 --> 00:31:33,769
That was the plan.

779
00:31:33,852 --> 00:31:35,729
So, I received the cash prize.

780
00:31:35,812 --> 00:31:38,690
And my mom came back
to hear the results of her physical.

781
00:31:38,774 --> 00:31:40,067
- - Right.
- So,

782
00:31:40,150 --> 00:31:44,321
we were eating beef short rib soup
at a restaurant in Seoul Station.

783
00:31:44,404 --> 00:31:46,323
I was enjoying it,

784
00:31:46,406 --> 00:31:50,285
but my mom kept giving me
all the ribs from her soup.

785
00:31:50,369 --> 00:31:52,204
"That's strange. It's not like her."

786
00:31:52,287 --> 00:31:53,539
That's what I thought.

787
00:31:53,622 --> 00:31:57,626
So I asked, "Mom, why aren't you eating
any of the ribs in your soup?"

788
00:31:57,835 --> 00:32:00,587
"I don't have any molars."

789
00:32:00,671 --> 00:32:02,005
- - That's what she said.
- I see.

790
00:32:02,339 --> 00:32:03,757
She needed dental implants,

791
00:32:04,341 --> 00:32:09,638
so her molars and the bone
surrounding them were removed.

792
00:32:09,721 --> 00:32:11,431
She told me she couldn't chew

793
00:32:11,515 --> 00:32:13,267
- - or eat meat.
- Okay.

794
00:32:13,559 --> 00:32:16,353
At first, I felt bad for her.

795
00:32:16,436 --> 00:32:19,439
But then I thought,
"Then why did she order short rib soup?"

796
00:32:19,523 --> 00:32:20,732
That occurred to me.

797
00:32:21,358 --> 00:32:24,570
I started thinking,
"Why is she telling me this?"

798
00:32:24,653 --> 00:32:27,322
I asked her,
"How much is it going to cost?"

799
00:32:27,489 --> 00:32:29,283
She said, "Seven million won."

800
00:32:30,951 --> 00:32:33,245
After paying the taxes on the cash prize,

801
00:32:33,328 --> 00:32:35,163
the remaining amount
would be 7.5 million won.

802
00:32:36,123 --> 00:32:38,667
So I asked for her bank info

803
00:32:39,084 --> 00:32:41,336
and my cash prize paid for my mom's teeth.

804
00:32:41,420 --> 00:32:43,380
- - For her dental implants.
- Yes.

805
00:32:43,463 --> 00:32:46,383
It was exchanged for two of her molars.

806
00:32:46,466 --> 00:32:49,845
My debt was still the same.

807
00:32:49,928 --> 00:32:53,265
- - The prize paid for your mother's teeth.
- Yes.

808
00:32:53,348 --> 00:32:55,225
She's still using those teeth.

809
